                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Upper left corner, in ink by a modern hand: <quote>A 223a.</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="SL1r" to="SL1r" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>Centre page: National Library stamp.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="252v" to="252v" scheme="folios"/>
                                <note>The entire page is filled with two repeated phrases in Latin by a medieval hand. The phrases contain some variation (<quote>Gaudenter prandi dum me nil soluere vidi</quote>;<quote> Cuicumque denegata est iusticia et regi et regno illata est iniuria</quote>) but appear to be pen-trials. In the outer margin is a paragraph by the same hand, largely illegible due to trimming, but several of the words match those from the repeated phrases next to it.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Upper part of page, four paragraps of contemporary additions. Three of them are in Latin and one in French; lower part of page in ink by an early modern hand: <quote>Bouchart</quote> (followed by a flourish or possible the number <quote>22</quote>).</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="unknown">
                                <p>Medieval or early modern binding. Brown leather over wooden boards. 5 double raised bands and endbands. Originally claps and bosses. Upper part of <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>: A medieval hand has written the titles in black on a parchment label, largely illegible due to damage. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>, ink on torn paper label: <quote>40</quote>, <quote>A 223a</quote>; National Library book label with current signum.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="310" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="225" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="70" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>Covers completely covered by sets of frames which contain a multitude of small stamped squares with different leaf and animal motifs.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather very worn and cracked, especially on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> where the bands are exposed. Part of the board on the front cover is also visible under the detached leather. Five holes after bosses on both <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>. Two groups of three nails on <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> all that remain of the clasps. Leather repaired in places.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1401">15h century</origDate>. Origin unknown. The first watermark may indicate southern <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName> or <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100208">Austria</placeName>, or possibly northern <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100036">Italy</placeName>. The second watermark seems to be most commonly found in nothern Italy. However, one of the medieval addtions on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> appears to be in French, which might also suggest <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100111">France</placeName> as an early provenance for the manuscript.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Based on the addition on <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/> (<quote>Bouchart</quote>) the manuscript is thought to have belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102693">Samuel Bochart</persName>, who visited <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100086">Queen Christina</persName> in <date when="1652"/>. He may then have given or sold the manuscript to the queen.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The earliest evidence for the manuscript in the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> is in Jaches' catalogue of 1695 (U 118:10), where it is listed as: <quote>157</quote>; and in Jaches' catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as <quote>120</quote>. The label on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> refers to the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e), where it is listed as: <quote>Phil. in fol. n<hi rend="super">o</hi> 40</quote>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                    </history>
